		\Large{\textbf{A quick guide to RMarkdown}} \\
	\end{center}
		
		\section{What is RMarkdown}
		Markdown is a simple formatting syntax for authoring HTML, PDF, and MS Word documents. You can embed and evaluate code chunks within these documents. Makdown documents have the extension $.Rmd$ and consist of three types of content:
		 
		\begin{enumerate}
		\item Metainformation like title and author, 
		\item code chunks and 
		\item text\\
		\end{enumerate}
		
		\section{Installation}
		For installing RMarkdown use one of the following commands in RStudio:
		\begin{lstlisting}
	install.packages("rmarkdown")
		\end{lstlisting}	
		
		If you want to generate PDF output, you will need to install LaTeX. In order to generate a report, use the "Knit" button in RStudio or use the \textit{render()} command.
		
		\section{Creating a RMarkdown Document}
		Using RStudio click on File - New File - R Markdown. Select your prefered Default Output Format. The default document will look like this will contain a header with the document title, author, creation date and output format.
		
		
